## Diagnosis

I don't have access to your codebase or the files you just shipped, so I cannot read the actual content and make the edits directly. I need you to share the relevant file(s) before I can make specific changes.

That said, I can give you everything else you need right now.

---

## Why This Keeps Happening

Em dashes slip through for two compounding reasons.

**1. LLM default register (the real root cause)**

Every large language model — including the one powering this assistant — is trained on formal editorial prose where em dashes are extremely common. Unless a system prompt or explicit instruction constrains it, the model defaults to that register on every generation call. The constraint does not "stick" across sessions; each conversation starts fresh with no memory of your voice rules.

**2. No automated enforcement gate**

Voice rules that live only in a style guide document are never enforced. There is no linter, no CI check, and no pre-commit hook that fails when an em dash character (`—`, U+2014) appears in content files. A rule without a gate is a suggestion.

---

## Fix — Two Parts

### Part 1: Automated enforcement (permanent solution)

Add a linter rule that fails on em dash characters in your content directory.

**`scripts/lint-voice.mjs`** (new file)
```js
import { readFileSync, readdirSync, statSync } from 'fs';
import { join } from 'path';

const CONTENT_DIRS = ['src/content', 'src/app'];
const BANNED = [
  { char: '\u2014', name: 'em dash (—)' },
  { char: '\u2013', name: 'en dash (–)' },   // add if also banned
];

function walk(dir) {
  const entries = readdirSync(dir);
  return entries.flatMap((entry) => {
    const full = join(dir, entry);
    return statSync(full).isDirectory() ? walk(full) : [full];
  });
}

const files = CONTENT_DIRS.flatMap(walk).filter((f) =>
  /\.(mdx?|tsx?|json)$/.test(f)
);

let violations = 0;

for (const file of files) {
  const lines = readFileSync(file, 'utf8').split('\n');
  lines.forEach((line, i) => {
    for (const { char, name } of BANNED) {
      if (line.includes(char)) {
        console.error(`[voice] ${name} at ${file}:${i + 1}`);
        console.error(`  > ${line.trim()}`);
        violations++;
      }
    }
  });
}

if (violations > 0) {
  console.error(`\n${violations} voice violation(s). Fix before committing.`);
  process.exit(1);
}

console.log('Voice lint passed.');
```

**`package.json`** — add to scripts:
```json
"lint:voice": "node scripts/lint-voice.mjs",
"lint": "next lint && npm run lint:voice"
```

**`.husky/pre-commit`** — add the check:
```sh
npm run lint:voice
```

Now a commit containing `—` in content files fails immediately with the file and line number.

---

### Part 2: Fix the existing content

Run this one-time sed command from your project root to find every em dash in your content directory and print the exact lines:

```bash
grep -rn $'\u2014' src/content/ src/app/
```

Then share those file paths and lines here, and I will rewrite every offending sentence with a compliant construction — comma, colon, parenthetical, or sentence break — per your voice rules.

---

## Principle

**A style rule without a machine-enforced gate is not a rule, it is a hope.**

Voice constraints must live in two places: the style guide (for humans) and an automated check (for machines). The LLM generating your content will revert to its training distribution the moment the constraint is absent from the prompt or the session resets. Enforcement cannot rely on memory — yours or the model's.
